FigureYa55panCancerTCGA + GTExTPMeasy_input.csvgganatogram

##Requirement description

Use the TPM values of the expression levels of the genes output by FigureYa55panCancer in TCGA+GTEx (easy_input. csv file) as input, and plot the expression distribution of the genes of interest in various organs using gganatogram.

gganatogramRhttps://github.com/jespermaag/gganatogramhttps://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/BlRT8I0RB1o-Mi4TEWhFrQ

https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/Uc6syOjFTOduxZfVaZRPqw

##Application scenarios

Introduction to the GGanatoramR package:< https://github.com/jespermaag/gganatogram >< https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/BlRT8I0RB1o-Mi4TEWhFrQ >

##Input file preprocessing

If your data has already been organized into the format of very easy input. csv, you can skip this step and enter Start Drawing.

Taking the TPM value of gene expression in TCGA+GTEx output from FigureYa55panCancer as an example (easy_input. csv file), it is necessary to match the cancer name in TCGA with the organ in the package.

Refer to GEPIA helps differential analysis:< http://gepia.cancer-pku.cn/help.html >On this basis, add the GAN of the gganatogram package and organize it into a TCGA_organ. txt file. Welcome to explore these corresponding relationships in the Xiaoya drawing group.

# TCGAGTEx(tumor)(normal)TPMCSV | Read CSV file containing TPM values for TCGA and GTEx tumor/normal samples
df <- read.csv("easy_input.csv", row.names = 1)

#  | View the first few rows to confirm data structure
head(df)
##   tissue type2    tpm
## 1    ACC tumor 4.1327
## 2    ACC tumor 4.9519
## 3    ACC tumor 3.0619
## 4    ACC tumor 2.7051
## 5    ACC tumor 1.9749
## 6    ACC tumor 3.1079
# "_" | Create a combined column in format "tissue_sampleType"
df$tt <- paste(df$tissue, df$type2, sep = "_")

# TPM | Group by combined column and calculate median TPM values
df.median <- aggregate(.~tt, df[,3:4], median)

# TCGA | Extract TCGA cancer abbreviations from combined column
df.median$TCGA <- str_split_fixed(df.median$tt, "_",2)[,1]

#  | Extract sample type from combined column
df.median$type <- str_split_fixed(df.median$tt, "_",2)[,2]

#  | Remove temporary combined column
df.median$tt <- NULL

### TCGAgganatogram
# TCGA_organ
# https://cn.bing.com/translator
TCGA.organ <- read.table("TCGA_organ.txt", sep = "\t", header = T)

# TCGA | Merge mapping table with median data to link TCGA abbreviations to organs
TCGA.organ.tpm <- merge(TCGA.organ[,c(1,4)], df.median, by = "TCGA")

# TCGA | Remove TCGA abbreviation column, no longer needed
TCGA.organ.tpm$TCGA <- NULL

#  | Filter out rows with empty organ names
TCGA.organ.tpm <- TCGA.organ.tpm[TCGA.organ.tpm$organ != "",]

# 
# TPM | Merge male organ template with TPM data
hgMale_key_tpm <- merge(hgMale_key, TCGA.organ.tpm, by = "organ")

# TPMvalue | Replace template's value column with TPM values for coloring
hgMale_key_tpm$value <- hgMale_key_tpm$tpm

# TPM | Remove original TPM column
hgMale_key_tpm$tpm <- NULL

#  | Export input file for male organogram
write.csv(hgMale_key_tpm,"very_easy_input_Male.csv", quote = F, row.names = F)

# 
# TPM | Merge female organ template with TPM data
hgFemale_key_tpm <- merge(hgFemale_key, TCGA.organ.tpm, by = "organ")

# TPMvalue | Replace template's value column with TPM values for coloring
hgFemale_key_tpm$value <- hgFemale_key_tpm$tpm

# TPM | Remove original TPM column
hgFemale_key_tpm$tpm <- NULL

#  | Export input file for female organogram
write.csv(hgFemale_key_tpm,"very_easy_input_Female.csv", quote = F, row.names = F)

very_easy_input_*.csv

##Start drawing

The value corresponding to very easy input. csv and organ.

-The first column is the name of the tissue and organ, which must be consistent with the organ in the package -In the second column, each type of organ is assigned a color -The system in which the third column organization is located -The fourth column of values can be gene expression levels or other clinical indicators. -Column 5: Tumor and Normal

The first and fourth columns are mandatory

Taking humans as an example, draw men and women separately to compare tumor and normal.

You can also draw for both men and women, and then photoshop it as half male and half female.

Other species can organize their data in the format of very easy input *. csv and apply it

#  | Load expression data for female organs
hgFemale_tpm <- read.csv("very_easy_input_Female.csv")

#  | View data structure
head(hgFemale_tpm)
##           organ  colour         type.x   value type.y
## 1 adrenal_gland #41ab5d          other 3.85310  tumor
## 2 adrenal_gland #41ab5d          other 3.60360 normal
## 3   bone_marrow #41ab5d          other 5.80170  tumor
## 4   bone_marrow #41ab5d          other 1.72290 normal
## 5         brain  purple nervous_system 4.90840  tumor
## 6         brain  purple nervous_system 5.41465  tumor
# type.ytype.x | Select column for grouping (type.y or type.x based on comparison needs)
hgFemale_tpm$type <- hgFemale_tpm$type.y

# 
# fillcolorvalue
# facet_wraptype
hgFemale <- gganatogram(data=hgFemale_tpm, 
                        fillOutline='white',    #  | Fill non-data organs with white
                        organism='human',       #  | Species: Human
                        sex='female',           #  | Gender: Female
                        fill="value") +         #  | Color by expression value
  facet_wrap(~type) +            #  | Facet by sample type
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "red") +  #  | Set color gradient from white to red
  labs(fill = "Log2(TPM + 1)") +  #  | Set legend title
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(-120, 0)) +  # Y | Limit Y-axis (exclude lower legs)
  theme_void()  #  | Hide axes

#  | Display female organ expression map
hgFemale

#  | Load expression data for male organs
hgMale_tpm <- read.csv("very_easy_input_Male.csv")

#  | View data structure
head(hgMale_tpm)
##           organ         type.x  colour  value type.y
## 1 adrenal_gland          other #41ab5d 3.8531  tumor
## 2 adrenal_gland          other #41ab5d 3.6036 normal
## 3   bone_marrow          other #41ab5d 5.8017  tumor
## 4   bone_marrow          other #41ab5d 1.7229 normal
## 5         brain nervous_system  purple 4.9084  tumor
## 6         brain nervous_system  purple 1.5366 normal
#  | Select column for grouping
hgMale_tpm$type <- hgMale_tpm$type.y

#  | Plot male organ expression map
hgMale <- gganatogram(data=hgMale_tpm, fillOutline='white', organism='human', sex='male', fill="value") + 
  facet_wrap(~type) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "green") +  #  | Set color gradient from white to green
  labs(fill = "Log2(TPM + 1)") + 
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(-120, 0)) +
  theme_void()

#  | Display male organ expression map
hgMale

# PDF | Combine male and female plots and save as PDF
pdf("gganatogram.pdf")
grid.arrange(hgFemale, hgMale, ncol=1)  #  | Arrange plots vertically
dev.off()  # PDF | Close PDF device

# type.x | Use type.x column as grouping variable (may represent different classification system)
hgFemale_tpm$type <- hgFemale_tpm$type.x

#  | Plot female organogram with predefined color values
gganatogram(data=hgFemale_tpm, 
            fillOutline='white',    #  | Fill non-data organs with white
            organism='human',       #  | Species: Human
            sex='female',           #  | Gender: Female
            fill="color") +         # color | Fill with color values from 'color' column
  facet_wrap(~type) +            # type | Facet by 'type' column
  theme_void()                   #  | Hide axes and background
